segments.text: We left off with you seeing it on how you felt about Vietnam or what you knew about Vietnam before I turned the tape over.
And I just asked you what you knew about Vietnam before you went to Vietnam.
And you were telling me that you had seen something on TV.
Not really.
I didn't really know that much when I was in high school.
So I went into the service when I was 20.
And but in high school we all knew we were aware of Vietnam, which I graduated my school in 63.
And so not, you know, not a whole lot, but we knew that what was happening so.
Didn't affect us a whole lot, but.
I was in college.
And because of the.
Because I was too busy doing things I shouldn't have been doing, like partying and not studying.
Got put on scholastic probation.
So you lost your S2A?
Yeah, 2S.
Went from 2S to 1A like overnight.
And then if you were 1A, you were gone.
Were you married then?
No.
So you didn't even have that, you couldn't even get out of the way because of being married?
You weren't engaged?
And you could get out that way.
I know, at that time, for a while you could.
Up through, well, Kennedy let you stay out without...
He had one child for a year.
They had more marriages, did you know?
More marriages in that period than they had in 1946 after the war ended, just to keep out of the war.
I had a lot of friends of mine that got married to stay out.
But you didn't.
Did you object to being sent to Vietnam?
No, I volunteered to go to Vietnam.
What had happened is...
We were at a base, at a strategic air command base, and they were taking everybody.
They had even taken all our M16s.
They had left us with carbines.
We were armed with carbines, which is a good weapon, but we weren't.
It was a World War II weapon.
And the M16s were all being sent to Vietnam.
At that time, the Air Force was the only one that had the M16 because it was an M16-issue weapon.
They had to go away with the M1?
No, yeah.
The Army had the M14.
What had happened to the M1?
Well, the M1 was obsolete.
It wasn't a repeating rocket, right?
Yeah, it was.
It wasn't semi-repeating, but not like the M16, was it?
Yeah, you could keep firing with an M1, but still it was real heavy, and it just wasn't effective as supposedly as the M14.
The Army adopted the M14 to replace the M1.
The Air Force, Colt,
offered the M-16 to the Army that turned it down because of the M-14.
They'd already taken it.
So the Air Force took the M-16.
When I got to Vietnam, you know, I had guys trade me M-14s for my rifle.
Wasn't the M-16 lighter weight than the M-14?
Yeah, a lot lighter.
So, but anyway, what had happened...
They were sending everybody to Vietnam when everybody knew that sooner or later you were going to go.
And we weren't real happy with who we was at anyway, so a bunch of us.
At that time, I was married.
And when I went to Vietnam, I'd been married seven months.
So you could have gotten out and gone to Vietnam anyway.
No.
No, you were married.
You got married after you went into service.
And took a girl from my hometown and
But anyway, we had been married that seven months.
Well, we got married May the 1st, and I got my orders in August.
And then I left like December the 22nd or 23rd.
Good timing thing, right before Christmas.
Right before Christmas.
Good timing.
Well, that's the Air Force for you.
The Air Force has timing like that.
So I spent Christmas guarding the perimeter around Bob Hope.
I didn't ever see him.
He really did come there?
Yeah, he was there, but we were securing the perimeter.
To make sure that he didn't get killed.
Or anybody else that was watching.
So we couldn't see him, but we...
Anyway, that was Christmas.
But yeah, we volunteered to go.
And we could go either two ways.
We could go just ourselves, or we could go to dog school and take a dog.
Either way.
So that...
You have been to air ground defense down at San Antonio.
Yeah.
I believe it's air base ground defense.
Yeah.
And that's on the LBJ Ranch.
Are you aware of that?
Part of the southern part of Israel?
I don't know that.
Yes.
You know, the first day.
He rented the property, I believe, to the Air Force.
The first day we were there, we walked in and they announced.
They said, how many of you are going to Tonsenute?
And there was several raised their hands.
And they said, as of this moment, Tonsenute Air Force Base is under ground attack.
And that was kind of shocking when you were not ever involved in anything like that.
You knew the possibility was there, but when you realized all of a sudden that it was reality.
Where were you when you found out about this?
We were at the combat school.
In San Antonio.
That made you really feel secure.
Made us really feel good.
They were, like I said, under attack at that time.
Then we went home from there and had, I don't know how many days before we left to go overseas.
But we weren't, I wasn't afraid, you know.
Well, did you, do you think that the, that school that you went to down in San Antonio, out of Lackland, it helped you in any, in the type of warfare?
Because I, from what I understand, I don't know whether it was in 66, but more recently they teach guerrilla warfare down there.
Yeah.
Did they teach any of it then?
No, not really.
Most everything we learned was, uh,
unarmed defense.
Yeah, some of the dealing with North Vietnamese customs like booby traps and different kinds of stuff like that, but it wasn't real thorough.
It was a new thing.
I remember our instructor in unarmed defense, he was crazy.
And
Everything was killed.
Everything he did had something to do with killing.
Nothing was bend somebody's arm and take them.
It was to kill them.

And I remember him telling us, and he really was crazy and everything, but I remember him telling us, he said, you'll know when you pass my test, when you step your foot back on the United States soil.
He said, until then, you won't know if you passed or not.
Obviously, you passed the test.
Well, so, some of us passed the test.
Well, there's some good logic to that.
Well, there is.
It kind of makes you, you know, I don't know, kind of gives you a funny feeling that, well, I've got to wait a year to see if I passed the test.
Kind of does.
But I never forgot that.
Well, obviously you didn't because you came back.
Yeah, right.
And there were many, many that did not come back.
Right.
Was Jane, Jane Fonda came over there at the time while you were there?
While I was there, she came, made her trip.
Would you like to tell me a little bit about that?
Well, morale wasn't really good.
Anyway, and because of the fact.
That we didn't have.
We didn't hear or feel the support.
From our own people, you know the Americans are at home.
We also were feeling that same.
You know that same kind of let down.
Of course you had it from from the enemy anyway.
But then again, all we heard was bad things.
from our own people.

And then Jane Fonda makes a trip to the North and starts feeling sorry and telling all those people over there, including the combat troops, how we are bloodthirsty and killing people when we shouldn't be, doing all the things that we shouldn't be doing.
And I don't know how many American GIs lost their lives because of her trip.
But I know a lot of them did because she fed all of the NARC energy to be able to fight that much harder because of the things she told them, because of the trips she made.
I mean, they like hearing that.
That's good stuff, good propaganda.
And it made them just fight that much harder.
And I think I blame our
for allowing her to make that trip.
To begin with, I felt like they should have shot her when she came back as a traitor.
I think she was as much a traitor as any traitor in the history of our country.
And I don't think she either should not have been allowed to come back or she should have been dealt with when she came back as a traitor.
But now I feel like that she shouldn't have ever been allowed to make the trip to begin with.
There are a lot of people that share your feelings against her.
There's a lot of people that don't have any.
She has an exercise deal.
And a lot of people that I've heard just in passing say, I won't touch it.
Yeah.
Because of what she did to our guys in Vietnam.
I don't know how the lady sleeps.
I really don't.
Because I know a lot of people lost their lives because of her.
So...
Well, you said that you felt that the war could have been won.
Do you think if Barry Goldwater had been elected president in 1964 instead of LBJ, because Barry Goldwater, if you recall, was called a warmonger, and he didn't know anything after all.
He was a brigadier general in the Air Force, but he didn't know anything.
Yeah.
about what was going on, and he really did know a lot about what was going on.
I think Barry Goldwater would have been a better president for the war than Lyndon Johnson.
I feel like Dwight Eisenhower would have been a better president than Lyndon Johnson, you know, as far as the war is concerned.
Or General MacArthur, or, you know, a lot of people.
I don't know if it would have been, I don't know if he would have been allowed to do

he wanted to do as a president you know congress would allow him to do um i don't know it's hard to say lbj and kennedy did what they wanted to do yeah they did so you know i can't see why goldwater right i don't know i you know it could have been done so much different you know that
You know, I mean, we've got bombs that'll take care of all of the country of Vietnam in one trip.
Well, Dwight Eisenhower threatened them when this thing first started.
He threatened to use atomic bombs.
Really?
And Congress said no.
Are you aware that this was never a declared war?
Oh, yeah.
That it was just the Gulf of Tonkin Accord that got them...
Bright.
Into the war?
There again, if you ask, and I know you understand this as well as I do, but if you ask the guys that were there, it was a war.
There's no question about the fact that it was a war.
But why are you bitter about that?
And they say, and a lot of other people, a lot of other Vietnam vets are bitter because some of them say that they didn't...
They weren't fighting for anything.
Well, I don't know why they say that.
I feel like, to begin with, that when you're born in this country, to begin with, that you, as a male, you're born with an obligation.
Not because I'm unusually patriotic or anything like that, but I believe that you're born with an obligation in this country to serve, to defend it at any cost.
if you're called to do that.
I don't feel like it's up to me to decide whether that cause is just or not.
I feel like it's a decision that should be made by the people we appoint to do that.
And when I went, my daddy went before me, his father before him, and on down the line, our fathers, whether you go or not, somebody went to do it.
And I believe we're obligated to do that.
When we went over there, you didn't know how it was going to turn out.
I mean, you couldn't go over there in 1962 or 1966 and say, well, we're going to leave here and pull out in 1973.
Nobody knew that.
So how are you going to predict that?
So you've got to go over there and fight for a cause.
You go over and fight because you were asked to do that by your country.
I don't think we need to question the president or we need to question Congress when we're sent to go somewhere to fight.
I'm very, very bitter at the deserters during that time.
And I'm very, very bitter...
and our political process for pardoning them.
I don't think that should have been done.
I think they should have went to jail.
I think if we ever have another war, they're going to do that same thing again because they got away with it.
I just believe that.
I believe everybody that died in Vietnam died with a...
a sense of duty, and I think they were fighting as hard as they could fight when they died.
And I think they were doing it, and I think they had pride in their uniform, and I think they had pride in the flag.
Were you aware that college graduates were getting out of the service by
Using technology and medical lying, actually lying, to keep from going into service?
Because their idea was that the people who, the lower class, uneducated people should go and do their dirty work.
Sure.
That's, you know, I guess that's a sign of the times, kind of.
But, and, you know, that's a, they're the ones that's got to live with it.
You know, I don't, I don't, I know people that lied about
medical things that weren't college graduates, you know, that were high school graduates that lied to get out of being drafted and get out of going to the service.
And I personally know people that did that.
I think that's something we can't control.
I don't think I can control it.
I don't think anybody else that's going to always go on.
I think I'm going to have to live with it, as you said.
Yeah.
You said you've read, you're familiar with Phil Caputo?
Yeah.
He was a college graduate who went into the Marines after he had, because he really didn't know what he was getting into.
And when he came back to the United States, he stayed out.
Have you read his book?
Yeah, I have.
Some time ago.
before the movie ever came out.
Do you remember enough about the book to remember how he...
Were the things that he wrote in there pretty standard for what you were aware of in Vietnam?
I think so.
I think so.
I think it was pretty much...
I remember... You know, I was captivated by...
There's...
I can read a book about Vietnam.
I cannot watch a movie about Vietnam.
And I can enjoy it.
I'm very, very much against Vietnam movies.
Why is that?
Because, well, I've never seen any of them to begin with.
That was a stupid question, wasn't it?
Well, no, not really.
I have seen, I've never had a desire to watch them for no particular reason.
And, you know, the next vet may say, well, I watch them all, you know, I enjoy watching them all.
But me personally, I've watched Tour of Duty from time to time.
I think it's not realistic in a lot of ways.
It's a soap opera, I think.
But stuff like Platoon, stuff like that, I've never seen.
Good Morning Vietnam.
I saw Good Morning Vietnam.
Pretty realistic.
I didn't know anything about the disc jockeys and that sort of thing.
But a lot of it was pretty realistic.
I kind of enjoyed it.
But it was funny.
Probably the lighter side of Vietnam, but with the undercurrent of the true Vietnam still being there.
Platoon, those type of movies, Deer Hunter, I've never seen none of those.
Here, not very long ago, I bought a movie, rented a movie, Platoon, and I don't even know why I did it.
I watched about half of that movie, maybe not half.
And that was more than I wanted to watch.
And halfway through it, and I was watching it by myself.
I shut it off.
I had a real, real bad reaction to that movie.
And I told my wife, I said, that right there is the reason that I don't watch that garbage.
Because it's not anything but garbage.
It wasn't like it?
No, it could have been in certain situations, but Vietnam movies like Platoon, which was the best picture, depicts the Vietnam veteran as a drug pothead, an acid head.
And full of foul language, you know, just in a sadist.
And that's not the way every Vietnam veteran in Vietnam was.
And I don't think it's fair, and I don't think it's wrong.
And it makes me very, very angry.
Super, super angry.
And I didn't know it until I watched that.
But there was a reason I never had wanted to see them.
I guess that's part of it.
So, what you're saying, this is 1989, and you're still dealing with some of the feelings that you had going back to 1966 and 67.
Yeah, yeah.
I reacted really, really, really bad to that movie.
In fact, I apologized to my wife for the way I reacted to that movie.
I broke down from that movie.
And really, it really affected me very, very badly.
So, you know, and like I said, the next veteran may not even bother.
You mentioned, you brought up the drug situation one, and you mentioned that in the platoon they did, I've seen the movie, and they did, I was not impressed with it, I did not like it.
Of course, I had not been through what you've been through, but I was totally impressed, especially since I had it.
Well, a lot of people must have liked it to be a best picture.
Well, probably our teenage population probably is enough to throw it into the bestseller.
What was the drug, what did you find the drug situation at this large base?
Saw a lot of the drugs, you know.
We had customs.
Security police does handle customs in foreign countries.
But, I mean, it was a joke.
We checked like every fifth guy.
The ones of us that pulled that duty.
Did you have dogs?
No, we didn't use dogs and customers.
The only thing we used dogs for was, they were all kill dogs.
Dogs, I'm sorry?
All kill dogs.
Kill?
Yeah, that's all we knew how to do.
Any drug or bomb dogs?
We had bomb dogs.
We started using those after we got a few things blown up in our gate.
So those bomb dogs really did...
They did a good job.

And yet you never hear anything, nothing's been heard about it in the news media, nothing's been said about these things that you had and the conditions that you lived under, nothing's been said about it because of the politicians.
When did you, when you were, well, you mentioned something about a heroin deal.
Yeah, the drugs.
The drugs we saw, you know, we checked every fifth guy.
We didn't have time to mess with all those guys.
You'd find all kinds of things.
You'd find guys trying to get out with claymore mines, with grenades, with marijuana, with heroin, with opium.
What?
Claymores.
It's a mine that you set that sweeps an area.
It's a bomb, a mine.
And they use it?
Oh, they try to take them home.
The drugs?
Drugs, bombs, grenades on the plane.
So you had to start searching them on the plane?
No, we searched them before they got on.
Every fifth guy.
So four in there got by with no telling what they had.
But anyway.
Did they know that it was every fifth guy you checked?
Or did they ever rotate numbers?
No, they didn't know.
Nobody cared.
And the guys didn't care.
They were going home.
So did it upset, did this movie, that platoon about showing the drug problem, did it upset you because of the, did it depict the drug problems you were aware of?
No.
The thing that bothers me about it, it depicts a Vietnam veteran as a nasty hit.
I mean, as a, you know, there was lots of drug problems in Vietnam.
You were upset about the generalization saying that everybody was.
Well, and that everybody was uncontrollably on drugs.
That's what I'm saying, everybody, that's a generalization.
That's not true, yeah.

There was guys, there was guys that used drugs that if you can put yourself in a situation where you're in a combat situation, you're sitting out in a muddy hole and it's raining so hard that you can't see,
you've got someone out there that wants to kill you.

And at the same time, they're telling you at home that you're a baby killer and that you're a sadist and that you're a slob for being there and that you shouldn't have ever been born and all this kind of stuff.
And then you're sitting there and your morale is below ground level.
And you know you've got drugs, you've got marijuana right there in your hand, and you know all you've got to do is smoke that.
or take it, or smoke some opium, and you're going to feel really good for a little while.
That's what most people are going to do.
They're going to take the opium right now.
You can't really blame them for it.
There's a lot of instances guys use drugs that I can condone.
Just to feel good just for a little while.
When you feel so bad and so let down from everything,
from everything around you, then that high for a little while has worked quite a bit.
We had the opium problem.
We found a civilian one night that had an estimated $3 million worth of opium.
We weren't allowed to keep it.
We wasn't allowed to follow it up.
We thought it was fixing to be loaded on a civilian aircraft.
We weren't allowed to follow it up for, I don't know why, but we wanted to find out where it was going.
And then we took it back to headquarters and the Vietnamese QC, Quang Cong, took it away from us.
And they allowed them to take it from us.
They wouldn't have taken it from us if we hadn't have just given it to them.
But we weren't going to.
And it was almost fixing to cause a
a war right there.
Right.
But we were ordered to give the opium to them.
And I'm sure they either sold it or used it.
You mentioned a while back about the Purple Heart.
This guy got the Purple Heart one actually.
He should have received medals for...
He should have received the ones the major got.
Well, there was a high...
There's a lot of guys that got medals for doing all kinds of stuff.
I knew a guy that got the Medal of Honor.
And he told me that he, you know.
He said they needed a hero.
So he got the Medal of Honor.
So he didn't feel like he really didn't feel like he really.
I feel like he probably did, but he doesn't feel like he deserves the Medal of Honor.
Didn't know he was going to get it until he seen the states thought he's going to get reprimanded.
He was in charge of the helicopter outfit.
And they had a bunch of helicopters that made an attack in the DMZ.
And when they did,
Every helicopter he had got shot at, including his, and lost a lot of men.
Do you remember his name?
No, I don't.
And he was wounded.
But he shot and killed a Russian officer in that attack.
And anyway, he got sent home.
And I don't remember his rank.
He was a lieutenant colonel or maybe a colonel.
And when he got home, they told him he needed to go to Washington.
He was really worried, and he got there.
His family was there.
They presented him with the Medal of Honor.
And he said he had no idea.
He thought he was in trouble.
I have a friend that was in the Army that received the Medal of Honor.
And he was a Holocaust pilot.
And he didn't feel that he deserved it either.
He said that he was just doing his duty the way he felt it.
He told me, he said...
Westmoreland, the politicians, Johnson, needed heroes really bad because of the attitude of the American people.
And he said he felt like that was the reason he got the Medal of Honor.
Now, I think the guy did a tremendous job.
They killed 400 or 500 enemy troops.
Fred Ferguson, this friend of mine, he took a helicopter gunships in and he...
protected them while they landed and brought up a whole bunch of, freed a whole bunch of prisoners.
And there's a book that's been written that he's listed in there, and he's told me before that he says, I didn't do nothing.
But I really, I think most of them do, and they are humble.
I think it's just a question of being humble.
There was guys that got medals, you know, for
Purple hearts were handed out pretty freely.
I knew guys that run through fences and got purple hearts, you know.
Wounds received.
Did you get a purple heart?
No, I didn't.
You didn't get wounded?
That's too fast.
I run backwards too fast.
You asked me about fragging.
Yeah, and you didn't know what I meant.
I didn't until you explained to me what it was, but I didn't see that happen.
I had a sergeant.
We had to pull what they called a QRT, which was a quick reaction team.
And what it was, if we came under attack, we were the first ones out.
And we had a sergeant that wouldn't lead us.
The reason he wouldn't was because he was afraid to.
Probably I would have, I hate to say this now, but a few years ago it wouldn't bother me, but I would have probably shot that sergeant.
if I'd ever got the chance.
But like I said, my hole probably wouldn't have been the only hole.
It probably would have been several.
Did he survive?
I don't know.
He was there when I left.
Oh, he was there when you left, yeah.
And then the tether fences came up right then, so right after I left.
So you weren't there when it got affected?
No, I missed it a few days.
Okay, you were very lucky.
Had they started the B-52 bombings before you left?
Oh, yeah.
Do you think they were effective at all?
Yes, I loved them.
Do you think they should have been started sooner?
Yeah, and I think they should have been done without any warning.
What do you mean, warning?
They always warned the villages before they struck the bombs.
How'd they do that?
They'd come in and tell them to get out of the villages.
The Americans were fixing the bottom.
That was like...
